00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,000
They are widely applicable to

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:22,000
all kinds of mathematical physics problems.

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,500
The most direct is electrostatic

7
00:00:26,500 --> 00:00:31,000
problems, electrostatic problems in two dimensions.

8
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:34,500
There are problems in theoretical physics which are

9
00:00:34,500 --> 00:00:38,000
mathematically equivalent to the electrostatic problem in two dimensions.

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,500
When I say incidentally the electrostatic problem in two dimensions, I

11
00:00:42,500 --> 00:00:47,000
don't mean that you have particles, charges moving in two dimensions

12
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:49,500
which interact with each

13
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:52,000
other with three-dimensional Coulomb forces.

14
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
I mean particles which move around, electric charges which

15
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
interact with each other with mathematical two-dimensional Coulomb forces.

16
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,500
Does anybody know what the Coulomb

17
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:05,000
force between particles is in two dimensions?

18
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:06,000
One over r?

19
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,000
One over r, not one over r squared.

20
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:12,000
How about the potential energy between a pair of particles?

21
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,000
You'd have to integrate that.

22
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Logarithm.

23
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Logarithm because the derivative of logarithm is one over r.

24
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:22,000
So in a world, a literal world,

25
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,500
where the lines of flux can't escape out into the

26
00:01:26,500 --> 00:01:31,000
third dimension, which are really forced to lie in the plane,

27
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:36,500
in such a world electrostatic problems would have Coulomb forces

28
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:42,000
which were one over r instead of one over r squared,

29
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,500
and the equations of electrostatics would be two-dimensional

30
00:01:46,500 --> 00:01:51,000
versions of the corresponding equations in three dimensions.

31
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,000
What are the equations of electrostatics?

32
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Let's just write them down

33
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,000
on the blackboard for a moment.

34
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:02,000
What do you describe an electrostatics problem by?

35
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:06,000
You describe it of course by an electric field.

36
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:07,500
But there's something simpler than

37
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:09,000
the electric field. What is it?

38
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Electric field is a vector. What's simpler than a vector?

39
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Charges.

40
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Well, charges, but a scalar.

41
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:19,000
A scalar.

42
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,000
The electrostatic potential,

43
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:24,500
the electrostatic potential, which is

44
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:28,000
sometimes, it goes under different names,

45
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,000
but let's call it phi.

46
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
What's the connection between phi and the electric field?

47
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
The gradient of phi is the electric field.

48
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Alright, so the gradient of phi is the electric field.

49
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,000
And what's the equation for

50
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
the electric field in electrostatics?

51
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Divergence of the electric field is?

52
00:02:58,000 --> 00:02:59,000
The charge density.

53
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,000
The charge density, right.

54
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:03,000
Charge density on the right-hand side,

55
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:05,000
or rho.

56
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:10,000
And we can rewrite that in terms of phi

57
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:12,000
by writing that it's, I'll write

58
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,000
this out in detail in a moment,

59
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,000
del squared phi equals rho.

60
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
Del dot phi is e.

61
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,000
Del dot e equals rho.

62
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:23,000
So del squared phi.

63
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:25,000
And what does del squared phi mean?

64
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:28,000
If we're in a two-dimensional world,

65
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
literally a two-dimensional world,

66
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:36,000
let's say with coordinates little x and little y,

67
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
then what is del squared?

68
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:40,500
Del squared is the second derivative

69
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:43,000
of phi with respect to x squared,

70
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,500
plus the second derivative of

71
00:03:45,500 --> 00:03:48,000
phi with respect to y squared.

72
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,000
And that on the right-hand side is rho.

73
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
If there's charge density, it's not zero,

74
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:56,000
but in places where there is no charge density,

75
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,000
in places where there is

76
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:00,000
no charge density, it's just zero.

77
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,000
You remember last time, I think it was last time,

78
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:09,000
we talked about this equation and its invariances.

79
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Conformal invariance.

80
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
This equation,

81
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
this equation is invariant or unchanged

82
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
by any change in the x, y coordinates,

83
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
any transformation to new coordinates,

84
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
x, y coordinates,

85
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
such that that transformation is conformal.

86
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:32,000
Conformal means?

87
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Angle-preserving.

88
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,000
In other words, that when you make a transformation,

89
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:41,000
when you, the angles,

90
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
well, let's just say the

91
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:45,000
angles in the new coordinate system

92
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
are perpendicular,

93
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:51,000
and that angles in new coordinates are exactly the same.

94
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Angles between curves in new coordinates

95
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,000
are the same as between the old coordinates.

96
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Conformal mappings.

97
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Those are conformal mappings,

98
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
and they are the kind of mappings that cartographers use

99
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:06,000
in order to preserve the shapes

100
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,000
and the angles on a map,

101
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,500
although they cannot in general

102
00:05:11,500 --> 00:05:14,000
preserve the sizes of things.

103
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
Okay, so that's an example of a,

104
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
of a place where conformal mappings occur.

105
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:21,000
Other places?

106
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
Fluid flow in two dimensions.

107
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,000
These are also equations of fluid flow.

108
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,000
All kinds of problems,

