00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:18,000
what is the condition?

277
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:21,000
If you want to have a nice mathematical framework

278
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:23,000
for complex functions,

279
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:25,000
and you want to have

280
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:27,000
the notion of a unique derivative,

281
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:30,000
maybe there is no good definition of the derivative,

282
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:33,000
but let's see what the conditions are

283
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:36,000
that the derivative,

284
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:39,000
the limit of delta w over delta z,

285
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,000
exists and is independent of

286
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:43,000
which direction you come in from.

287
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:46,000
Now I'm going to show you a sufficient condition,

288
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:49,000
you can go home and prove it's a necessary condition,

289
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:52,000
it is a necessary condition,

290
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:54,000
and it's almost as easy to

291
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:56,000
prove as what we will do,

292
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:59,000
but I'll leave it to you for homework.

293
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,000
To prove, what I'm going to do

294
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:05,000
is work out the necessary condition

295
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:08,000
by asking that the ratio,

296
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,000
delta w over delta z,

297
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:13,000
is the same if you come in from the x-axis

298
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
along the x-axis,

299
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:17,000
or if you come in along the y-axis.

300
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:20,000
In other words, if your delta z

301
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:23,000
is along the x-axis or along the y-axis,

302
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:25,000
that you get the same answer.

303
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,000
It is then not hard to prove

304
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,000
that if that's satisfied,

305
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,000
that no matter what direction you come in from,

306
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:33,000
you get the same answer.

307
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:34,000
So I'll do the simple thing,

308
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:35,000
you can do the slightly more complicated thing,

309
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,000
it's only a little bit of algebra,

310
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:39,000
but I don't like doing

311
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,000
too much algebra on the blackboard.

312
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:45,000
Okay, let's calculate

313
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:50,000
delta w by delta z.

314
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:54,000
Now first of all, what is delta w?

315
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:57,000
w is u plus iv.

316
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Why don't we, let's not be babies,

317
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:03,000
let's call it dw by dz.

318
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:11,000
Whenever I teach pre-meds,

319
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:13,000
I'm not allowed to use calculus.

320
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:15,000
And so every time there's a derivative,

321
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:19,000
we call it delta w by delta z or whatever,

322
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:21,000
and then we're not officially using calculus,

323
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:23,000
and that's illegal.

324
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:25,000
But then I secretly tell them,

325
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
you realize that's a derivative,

326
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:31,000
and they say, yeah, yeah, we know.

327
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:33,000
But I'm always afraid if I use it

328
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,000
that they'll tell ombudsmen that I'm using calculus,

329
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:37,000
and I'm not going to use calculus in class.

330
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:39,000
Okay, so the change in w

331
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
divided by the change of z,

332
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:44,000
and what of course is that?

333
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:47,000
That's equal to the derivative of,

334
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:50,000
or the change, the small change in u

335
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:54,000
plus the small i times the small change in v

336
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:57,000
as you go from here to here.

337
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:01,000
Derivative of the differential of u plus iv

338
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:03,000
divided by the differential of x plus i.

339
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:05,000
Okay.

340
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:08,000
dy.

341
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:10,000
Okay, that's very straightforward.

342
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:12,000
Now let's calculate it if

343
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:14,000
I come in along the x-axis.

344
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:17,000
If I come in along the x-axis,

345
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:20,000
then dy is equal to zero.

346
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:21,000
Okay?

347
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:23,000
dy is equal to zero if

348
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:25,000
I come in along the x-axis,

349
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:28,000
and so this must equal,

350
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:31,000
coming in along the x-axis,

351
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:33,000
it must equal du by dx plus i d.

352
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:34,000
Okay?

353
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:37,000
So I'm going to calculate the derivative of u

354
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,000
plus i dv by dx.

355
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:42,000
Since we're keeping y fixed and not varying y,

356
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:45,000
this is the same as the partial derivative of u

357
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:47,000
with respect to x

358
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:50,000
plus i times the partial derivative of v

359
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:52,000
with respect to x.

360
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:53,000
Oops.

361
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:56,000
With respect to x.

362
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:58,000
Okay, is that clear?

363
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:00,000
Good.

364
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:02,000
Now let's come in along the y-axis.

365
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:04,000
dx is equal to zero.

366
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:06,000
dy is not zero.

367
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:08,000
And the partial derivatives are

368
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:10,000
partial derivatives with respect to y.

369
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:13,000
So let's see what that has to equal.

370
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:16,000
If, under the presumption,

371
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:18,500
that dw by dz doesn't depend

372
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:21,000
on which direction you come in from.

373
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:23,000
Okay, so let's see what we have to have.

374
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:25,000
Then we have to have

375
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:27,000
1 over i.

376
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:29,000
The 1 over i comes from the i.

377
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:30,000
dx is going to be zero.

378
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:31,000
There's a 1 over i from the 1 over i.

379
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:34,000
multiplying dy.

380
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:37,000
And then we'll have partial

381
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:40,000
of u with respect to y.

382
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:43,000
And then i over i

383
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:47,500
will just give you derivative

384
00:17:47,500 --> 00:17:52,000
of v with respect to y.

385
00:17:52,000 --> 00:17:54,000
u and v are real.

386
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:56,000
I neglected to say so.

387
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:58,000
It may have been obvious.

388
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:00,000
u and v are real.

389
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,000
It's w which is complex.

390
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:04,000
x and y are real.

391
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:06,000
z is complex.

392
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:09,000
It's at least a necessary condition.

393
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:11,000
It happens to be sufficient also.

394
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,000
But it's at least a necessary condition

395
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:17,000
that this expression equals this expression.

396
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:19,000
Necessary for what?

397
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:21,000
Necessary that the derivative

398
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:24,000
not depend on which direction you're coming in from.

399
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:25,000
Okay?

400
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:28,000
Now, so let's take the real and imaginary part.

401
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:29,000
Whenever you have an equation,

402
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:32,000
that involves real and imaginary parts,

403
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:34,000
it really stands for two equations.

404
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:38,000
Equating the real part and equating the imaginary part.

405
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:40,000
So, let's start with the real part.

406
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:41,000
Here's a real part.

407
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:44,000
That's got to equal this.

408
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:53,000
du by dx must equal bv by dy.

409
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:54,000
And what about the other one?

410
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:57,000
The other one says,

411
00:18:57,000 --> 00:18:58,000
let's see,

412
00:18:58,000 --> 00:18:59,000
that's the real part.

413
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:01,000
Here's the imaginary part.

414
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:02,000
Let's put it over here.

415
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:12,000
idv by dx equals 1 over i du by dy.

416
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:14,000
idv by dx has to be

417
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:16,000
1 over i du by dy.

418
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:19,000
That's equating the imaginary parts.

419
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:23,000
Let's multiply both sides by i

420
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:27,000
and use the fact that i squared is minus 1.

421
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:31,000
So we get two equations.

422
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:32,000
There are two,

423
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:33,000
they're not the same incidentally,

424
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:34,000
look at them.

425
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:38,000
One says du by dx equals dv by dy.

426
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:41,500
And the other says du

427
00:19:41,500 --> 00:19:45,000
by dy equals dv by dx.

428
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:48,000
No, minus dv by dx.

429
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:50,000
One of them has a minus sign,

430
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:52,000
the other doesn't.

431
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:01,000
If these equations are not true,

432
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:03,500
then the derivative doesn't exist

433
00:20:03,500 --> 00:20:06,000
in a meaningful and unique way.

434
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:08,000
If they are both true,

435
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:13,000
then the function w of z has a derivative,

436
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:15,000
and the derivative is well defined,

437
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:17,000
and the function is called analytic.

438
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:19,000
Just a name.

439
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:20,000
When a function,

440
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:22,000
on a complex function of a complex variable,

441
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:25,000
has a unique derivative from every direction,

442
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:27,000
it's called analytic at that point.

443
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:32,000
If it's analytic everywhere,

444
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:34,000
then it's called entire.

445
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:35,000
All sorts of names,

446
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:36,000
meromorphic, holomorphic,

447
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:38,000
I never understood what they meant.

448
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:40,000
Holomorphic is analytic.

449
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:42,000
No, meromorphic allows poles and...

450
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:44,000
Holomorphic is the same as analytic.

451
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:46,000
Yeah, holomorphic is the same as analytic.

452
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:47,000
I think that's right,

453
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:49,000
I don't remember.

454
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:52,000
There's fancy names for everything.

455
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:54,000
I've learned recently that a mapping

456
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:56,000
which takes a point to a point

457
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:58,000
is called a bijection or something.

458
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
That's right.

459
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:04,000
Well, we do diffeomorphisms and all that.

460
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:05,000
Yeah, yeah, yeah,

461
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:14,000
these coordinate transformations of diffeomorphisms.

462
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:18,000
Right, but all they are is coordinate transformations.

463
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:20,000
Nice smooth ones.

464
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:24,000
Okay, so we have now the necessary and sufficient conditions

465
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:26,000
for a function to be analytic,

466
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:28,000
every place where these are satisfied.

467
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:30,000
Let's look at these equations a little more,

468
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:32,000
just for fun,

469
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
see what they say.

470
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:41,000
They're coupled equations for u and v.

471
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:42,500
Can we uncouple them and

472
00:21:42,500 --> 00:21:44,000
write an equation just for u

473
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:46,000
and an equation just for v?

474
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:47,000
Yes, we can.

475
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:49,000
Here's the trick.

476
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:53,000
Let's differentiate this equation with respect to x.

477
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:56,000
That gives us d second u,

478
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:58,000
by dx squared,

479
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:00,000
the second partial derivative with respect to x,

480
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:03,000
and that's equal to dv,

481
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:06,000
that's equal to the second derivative of v

482
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:08,000
with respect to x,

483
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:10,000
with respect to y.

484
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:13,000
The mixed partial derivative with respect to x and y.

485
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:17,000
Let's differentiate this one with respect to y.

486
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:19,000
That's d second u,

487
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:22,000
by dy squared.

488
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:25,000
That's equal to minus

489
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,000
d second v,

490
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:29,000
by dx by dy.

491
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:34,000
That's the same as that except for a minus sign,

492
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:37,000
so it follows that we can eliminate it,

493
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:43,000
and one equation is d second u,

494
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:46,000
by dx squared,

495
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:49,000
minus, sorry,

496
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:52,000
this is u.

497
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:54,000
Yeah, no, no, we just, we have to,

498
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:57,000
just add them.

499
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:06,000
Add them and the right hand side will go away.

500
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:09,000
Well, that's a familiar equation.

501
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:14,000
That's just Laplace's equation in two dimensions.

502
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:18,000
So, a necessary condition.

503
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:21,000
Well, something looks a little like your curl equation, too.

504
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:23,000
It does.

505
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:24,000
So it's something, sort of, curl-ish.

506
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:26,000
Well, that's,

507
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:27,000
this one,

508
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:29,000
yeah, that sort of is it,

509
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:32,000
is it, is it the derivative is curl-free,

510
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:33,000
in some sense.

511
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:34,000
Yeah.

512
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:36,000
One of them is curl and the other is divergence,

513
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:39,000
depending on which way you define the components.

514
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:44,000
Uh,

515
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:45,500
yeah, if you think of u

516
00:23:45,500 --> 00:23:47,000
and v as components of a vector,

517
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:49,000
actually you have to think of u and minus v

518
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:51,000
as the components of a vector,

519
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:52,000
then what it says is

520
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:53,000
that the curl and the divergence,

521
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:57,000
and the divergence of the vector vanishes.

522
00:23:57,000 --> 00:23:59,000
Okay, so that's this equation,

523
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:01,000
and if you do exactly the same thing,

524
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:03,000
we differentiate this one now,

525
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:04,000
instead of with respect to x,

526
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:07,000
we differentiate it with respect to y,

527
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:10,000
and differentiate this one with respect to x,

528
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:14,000
what we get is exactly the same equation for v,

529
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:17,000
d second v by dx squared,

530
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:20,000
plus d second v by dy squared,

531
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:22,000
equals zero.

532
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:25,000
So first of all, an analytic function,

533
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:26,000
w of z,

534
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:32,000
contains two real solutions of the Laplace equation.

535
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:34,000
That's interesting to know.

536
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:35,000
Every analytic function,

537
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:38,000
every function which has a derivative,

538
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,000
and incidentally,

539
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:43,000
most of the simple functions that you write down,

540
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:45,000
I'll give you some examples as we go along,

541
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:47,000
most of the simple functions that

542
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:49,000
you would be likely to write down,

543
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:50,000
are analytic.

544
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:52,000
So in this way,

545
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:55,000
you can generate a large family

546
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:58,000
of solutions of the Laplace equation.

547
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:01,000
Now it's not sufficient to have

548
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:04,000
two solutions of the Laplace equation.

549
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:06,000
Two solutions of the Laplace equation

550
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:09,000
are just two solutions of the Laplace equation.

551
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:12,000
These equations link them together.

552
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:14,000
So in fact,

553
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:19,000
it's not every pair of Laplace functions

554
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:21,000
define an analytic function.

555
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:23,000
